    "Extended Summary": {
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "data": {
            "inline": [
              {
                "type": "Words",
                "data": {
                  "value": "A quadrilateral mesh consists of a grid of vertices. The dimensions of this array are (*meshWidth* + 1, *meshHeight* + 1). Each vertex in the mesh has a different set of \"mesh coordinates\" representing its position in the topology of the mesh. For any values (*m*, *n*) such that 0 <= *m* <= *meshWidth* and 0 <= *n* <= *meshHeight*, the vertices at mesh coordinates (*m*, *n*), (*m*, *n* + 1), (*m* + 1, *n* + 1), and (*m* + 1, *n*) form one of the quadrilaterals in the mesh. There are thus (*meshWidth* * *meshHeight*) quadrilaterals in the mesh.  The mesh need not be regular and the polygons need not be convex."
                }
              }
            ],
            "inner": []
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "data": {
            "inline": [
              {
                "type": "Words",
                "data": {
                  "value": "A quadrilateral mesh is represented by a (2 x ((*meshWidth* + 1) * (*meshHeight* + 1))) numpy array *coordinates*, where each row is the *x* and *y* coordinates of one of the vertices.  To define the function that maps from a data point to its corresponding color, use the "
                }
              },
              {
                "type": "Directive",
                "data": {
                  "value": [
                    "set",
                    "_",
                    "cmap"
                  ],
                  "domain": null,
                  "role": "meth"
                }
              },
              {
                "type": "Words",
                "data": {
                  "value": " method.  Each of these arrays is indexed in row-major order by the mesh coordinates of the vertex (or the mesh coordinates of the lower left vertex, in the case of the colors)."
                }
              }
            ],
            "inner": []
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "data": {
            "inline": [
              {
                "type": "Words",
                "data": {
                  "value": "For example, the first entry in *coordinates* is the coordinates of the vertex at mesh coordinates (0, 0), then the one at (0, 1), then at (0, 2) .. (0, meshWidth), (1, 0), (1, 1), and so on."
                }
              }
            ],
            "inner": []
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Paragraph",
          "data": {
            "inline": [
              {
                "type": "Words",
                "data": {
                  "value": "*shading* may be 'flat', or 'gouraud'"
                }
              }
            ],
            "inner": []
          }
        }
      ],
